description: Including some without a band on the shoulder. Under baccharis and among rocks

Note that true Vespericola karokorum is covered with relatively long "hairs" over periostracum. Previously identified Karok Snails on this site are NOT true V. karokorum.   The specimen pictured was sympatric with Plethodon elongatus, Monadenia fidelis, Haplotrema vancouverense, Ensatina eschscholtzii, Lobaria pulmonaria, Douglas-fir, Tanoak; found in mossy talus  and under downed woody debris in area of Donahue Flat, above  intersections of Bark Shanty and Ishi Pishi Roads off USFS Road 13N18 off of G-O Road, in area known to US Forest Service staff as Donahue Thin Project.  This species is very limited in distribution and was proposed in 1973 for Endangered Species Status. It has never been given any protected status and almost nothing has been published on the species since its original description. There exists one white-paper report in USFS files with locality data and status as of late 1970's that has never been published.
